Ticks & labels¶

In [17]:
# import required module 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt 

# assign coordinates 
x = y = [i for i in range(0, 10)] 
ax = plt.axes() 

# depict illustration 
plt.plot(x, y, color="lime") 

# setting ticks for x-axis 
ax.set_xticks([2, 4, 6, 8, 10]) 

# setting ticks for y-axis 
ax.set_yticks([1, 3, 5, 7, 9]) 

plt.show()
In [19]:
# import required module 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt 

# assign coordinates 
x = y = [i for i in range(0, 10)] 
ax = plt.axes() 

# depict illustration 
plt.plot(x, y, color="lime") 

# setting ticks for x-axis 
ax.set_xticks([2, 4, 6, 8, 10]) 

# setting label for x tick 
ax.set_xticklabels(['AA', 'BB', 'CC', 'DD','EE']) 

# setting ticks for y-axis 
ax.set_yticks([1, 3, 5, 7, 9]) 

# setting label for y tick 
ax.set_yticklabels(['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E']) 

plt.show()
In [20]:
# import required modules 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt 
import numpy as np 
import math 

# assign coordinates 
x = np.arange(0, math.pi*2, 0.05) 
y = np.sin(x) 
ax = plt.axes() 
plt.xlabel("x-axis") 
plt.ylabel("y-axis") 

# depict illustration 
plt.plot(x, y, color="lime") 

# setting ticks for x-axis 
ax.set_xticks([0, 2, 4, 6]) 

# setting ticks for y-axis 
ax.set_yticks([-1, 0, 1]) 

# setting label for y tick 
ax.set_yticklabels(["sin(-90deg)", "sin(0deg)", "sin(90deg)"]) 

plt.show()

# importing modules 
import numpy as np 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt 

# X-axis values 
x = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8] 

# Y-axis values 
y1 = [0, 3, 6, 9, 12, 15, 18, 21, 24] 
# Y-axis values 
y2 = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8] 

plt.xlim([0,2])

plt.ylim([0,2])

# Function to plot 
plt.plot(y1, label ="y = x") 
plt.plot(y2, label ="y = 3x") 



# Function add a legend 
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor =(0.75, 1.15), ncol = 2) 

# function to show the plot 
plt.show()

Bar Plots¶

In [29]:
#plt.bar(x, height, width, bottom, align)
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt 


# creating the dataset
data = {'C':20, 'C++':15, 'Java':30, 
		'Python':35}
courses = list(data.keys())
values = list(data.values())

fig = plt.figure()

# creating the bar plot
plt.bar(courses, values, bottom = 0, color ='maroon', 
		width = 0.4)

plt.xlabel("Courses offered")
plt.ylabel("No. of students enrolled")
plt.title("Students enrolled in different courses")
plt.show()
